10:08.808 --> 10:13.012 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Naval activity by the United
States prompted another negative
reaction from Beijing today,

10:13.012 --> 10:20.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as Pentagon Chief Ashton Carter
went on an unusual voyage with a
U.S. ally.

10:20.453 --> 10:25.158 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The fighter pilots on the U.S.
Theodore Roosevelt went about
their business today. But this

10:25.158 --> 10:29.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time, Defense Secretary Ash
Carter and his Malaysian
counterpart were on board
watching

10:29.295 --> 10:33.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as the aircraft carrier
plied the South China Sea.

10:33.933 --> 10:40.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The ship and its escort group
were moving some 150 nautical
miles south of the Spratly

10:40.073 --> 10:47.146 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Islands. They fall in a vast
area that's claimed by Beijing.
China also claims a 12-mile
territorial

10:47.146 --> 10:52.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
zone around artificial islands
in the Spratlys, including
airstrips and other military
facilities.

10:52.886 --> 10:58.191 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A U.S. Navy destroyer challenged
that 12-mile zone last week.
Today, the Chinese Foreign

10:58.191 --> 11:01.995 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ministry again criticized
the American actions.

11:01.995 --> 11:04.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HUA CHUNYING, Spokeswoman,
Chinese Ministry of Foreign
Affairs (through translator):
China

11:04.764 --> 11:09.702 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has consistently respected all
countries' freedom of navigation
under international

11:09.702 --> 11:15.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
law. What we oppose is waving
the banner of freedom of
navigation to push forward the

11:15.108 --> 11:19.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
militarization of the South
China Sea. We hope the relevant
actions and intentions of

11:19.312 --> 11:23.249 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the U.S. can be made more
open and transparent.

11:23.249 --> 11:27.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Just
yesterday, defense ministers
from Southeast Asia ended a
meeting

11:27.220 --> 11:32.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in Malaysia without issuing a
final statement. It was scrapped
after China objected to
mentioning

11:32.559 --> 11:36.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the sea dispute. Secretary
Carter was there.

11:36.396 --> 11:40.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ASHTON CARTER, U.S. Defense
Secretary: I reminded everyone
that the United States doesn't
take

11:40.133 --> 11:46.372 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
sides in these maritime
disputes, but we do take the
side of peaceful resolution
under

11:46.372 --> 11:48.841 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
international law.

11:48.841 --> 11:51.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Today, Carter
said his carrier visit is a
response to regional fears about

11:51.778 --> 11:54.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Chinese behavior.

11:54.814 --> 11:58.184 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He called it -- quote -- "a sign
of the critical role the United
States' military power plays

11:58.184 --> 12:01.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in a very consequential region."

12:01.354 --> 12:06.392 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S. officials say the Navy
means to continue challenging
the Chinese territorial claims,

12:06.392 --> 12:09.963 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on a regular basis.

12:09.963 --> 12:12.999 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Joining me now to help us
understand the United States'
recent activity in the South
China

12:12.999 --> 12:16.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sea and what it means is Bonnie
Glaser, director of the China
Power Project at the Center for

12:16.302 --> 12:19.372 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Strategic and International
Studies in Washington.

12:19.372 --> 12:23.543 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, first, how big a deal is
this, if Ash Carter gets on a
very nice ship and decides

12:23.543 --> 12:27.313 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to take a cruise in
territorially disputed waters?

12:27.313 --> 12:30.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BONNIE GLASER, Center for
Strategic and International
Studies: Well, Secretary Carter
has done this

12:30.216 --> 12:34.854 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
previously, when he attended the
Shangri-La dialogue in June of
this year.

12:34.854 --> 12:40.259 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was on a P-8 surveillance
aircraft flying over the Malacca
Straits. So it's not unusual

12:40.259 --> 12:45.365 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for the United States secretary
of defense to be on a military
platform out in the South

12:45.365 --> 12:50.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
China Sea demonstrating to the
region that the United States
has an abiding interest

12:50.103 --> 12:52.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in peace and stability
in the region.

12:52.872 --> 12:57.110 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Is it a
provocative act to be in this
specific place at this time?

12:57.110 --> 13:00.513 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BONNIE GLASER: Undoubtedly, the
Chinese see it as a provocative
act, but I think that

13:00.513 --> 13:04.217 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the other nations in
the regions do not.

13:04.217 --> 13:10.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think if you look at Malaysia,
Vietnam, the Philippines, the
other claimants, they

13:10.356 --> 13:17.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are very happy to see the United
States' flag shown in the
region. They supported the
United

13:17.697 --> 13:23.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States exercising freedom of
navigation around what is called
Subi Reef, which is the
elevation,

13:23.569 --> 13:30.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the low-tide elevation that the
USS Lassen, a destroyer,
conducted a freedom of
navigation

13:30.309 --> 13:33.413 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
operation just a few days ago.

13:33.413 --> 13:36.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, this is something that the
region supports generally.

13:36.449 --> 13:40.353 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The freedom of
navigation idea, is it a right
that sort of use it or

13:40.353 --> 13:43.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lose it? If you don't use it, is
that kind of what we're
stressing here by having carrier

13:43.589 --> 13:45.958 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
groups go through?

13:45.958 --> 13:49.595 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BONNIE GLASER: The United States
has been doing this of course
for centuries. And since

13:49.595 --> 13:55.268 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
1979, it has had a freedom
of navigation program.

13:55.268 --> 14:02.375 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in fact, this is the
seventh what we call FONOP that
has been conducted since 2011

14:02.375 --> 14:07.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the South China Sea. And,
yes, I think if the Navy does
not sail through, and not

14:07.213 --> 14:14.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
just the U.S. Navy, but
Australia navy, Japan's navy
doesn't sail through waters that
are

14:14.721 --> 14:18.591 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
high seas, that they are not
territorial seas of other
countries, even in territorial
seas,

14:18.591 --> 14:21.828 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
we can sail through
making innocent passage.

14:21.828 --> 14:26.532 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, in fact, that is really
what we did in this case. We
sailed through a territorial

14:26.532 --> 14:33.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sea of China's Subi Reef. So,
yes, you have to exercise it or
other countries may claim

14:33.306 --> 14:36.876 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it and may try to
exclude other navies.

14:36.876 --> 14:40.379 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Speaking of
other countries and their
claims, what have the other
countries

14:40.379 --> 14:45.051 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the region that have vested
interests in these waters, what
have they been doing, besides

14:45.051 --> 14:48.521 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
just China and the United States
that get kind of pinned in this
conversation?

14:48.521 --> 14:54.594 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
BONNIE GLASER: Well, the
Philippines is trying to enhance
its capability to conduct what

14:54.594 --> 14:59.198 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we call better maritime domain
awareness, to know what's going
on inside its 200 nautical

14:59.198 --> 15:02.034 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
mile exclusive economic zone.

15:02.034 --> 15:07.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in fact Japan and the United
States has been providing some
capability. The same is

15:07.073 --> 15:12.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
true with Vietnam. And the
thinking here is that if other
claimants know what's going

15:12.011 --> 15:20.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on inside their waters, that the
Chinese will be less apt to use
coercion against them.

15:20.453 --> 15:25.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Diplomatically, there's also
some steps being taken. The
Philippines has taken a very
important

15:25.057 --> 15:31.130 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
case to the court under the U.N.
Convention of the Law of the
Sea, and there was just

15:31.130 --> 15:35.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an announcement today that the
merits of that case will be
heard at the end of November.

15:35.868 --> 15:39.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The court has already found
jurisdiction on a number of the
counts.

15:39.272 --> 15:43.009 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, next year, there is going to
be likely a ruling that will
come down and that will

15:43.009 --> 15:47.346 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
also have implications for the
behavior of China and other
countries going forward.

15:47.346 --> 15:50.116 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, does
China respect the decision of
that court?

15:50.116 --> 15:54.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BONNIE GLASER: China has already
said that this court doesn't
have jurisdiction and it

15:54.086 --> 15:57.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has said that its finding will
be null and void, it will reject
it.

15:57.990 --> 16:03.029 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I do think that China cares
about its international
reputation, and so there is

16:03.029 --> 16:08.634 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a possibility that China will
reconsider that as we go
forward. I hope other countries
will

16:08.634 --> 16:15.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
impose some more costs on China,
particularly in terms of its
coercive strategy in the region,

16:15.208 --> 16:20.313 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so that we can convince the
Chinese that they're playing at
an ineffective game.

16:20.313 --> 16:25.218 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They should have good relations
with their neighbors, rather
than exert their sovereignty

16:25.218 --> 16:29.822 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
claims over these rocks and
reefs in the South China Sea
that I think are less important

16:29.822 --> 16:32.525 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to Chinese interests
over the long run.

16:32.525 --> 16:36.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: How different
have China's actions been
compared to other people trying

16:36.395 --> 16:42.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to stake a claim? We had video
of newly developed airstrips on
some of these islands and even

16:42.068 --> 16:46.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
military armaments that are
really kind of ramping up.

16:46.672 --> 16:50.943 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BONNIE GLASER: The Chinese do
see themselves as playing
catchup, because every other
claimant

16:50.943 --> 16:55.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the South China Sea, with the
exception of Brunei, has an
airstrip.

16:55.481 --> 17:01.821 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have all conducted a small
amount of land reclamation. That
is taking a land feature

17:01.821 --> 17:05.558 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and making it a little bit
bigger. The Chinese went in
there and dredged an enormous
amount

17:05.558 --> 17:09.929 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of sand and built these very
large artificial islands.

17:09.929 --> 17:15.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So now the Chinese occupy the
largest land feature, which is
three times larger than

17:15.534 --> 17:22.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the largest natural-produced
island in the area. The Chinese,
the scope of what they

17:22.942 --> 17:28.381 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have done, and now they will
have four airstrips in the South
China Sea. Their capability
really

17:28.381 --> 17:31.250 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
outstrips every other claimant.

17:31.250 --> 17:33.452 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right,
Bonnie Glaser of the Center for
Strategic and International

17:33.452 --> 17:34.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Studies in Washington, thanks
so much for joining us.

17:34.453 --> 17:40.293 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
BONNIE GLASER: Thank you.

17:40.293 --> 17:51.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: During the
Cold War, the United States
built tens of thousands of
nuclear

17:51.437 --> 17:55.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weapons. Now that it's over and
with arms control treaties in
place, the arsenal has

17:55.074 --> 17:58.110 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shrunk significantly.

17:58.110 --> 18:03.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Departments of Defense and
Energy say the remaining bombs
need to be rebuilt, but

18:03.249 --> 18:08.454 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
critics say those departments
are building new nuclear bombs
and spending too much money.

18:08.454 --> 18:12.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Veteran correspondent Jamie
McIntyre, now Al-Jazeera
America's national security
correspondent,

18:12.325 --> 18:16.429 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
went on special assignment for
the "NewsHour" to examine the
claims.

18:16.429 --> 18:21.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The story was produced in
partnership with the Pulitzer
Center on Crisis Reporting.

18:21.567 --> 18:28.207 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: At Eglin Air
Force Base, a solitary F-15
takes to the skies over the

18:28.207 --> 18:38.751 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
swamps of Western Florida on a
mission that hearkens back to
the Cold War.

18:38.751 --> 18:43.489 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It looks like any old-fashioned
gravity bomb as it falls to
earth. But what you're seeing

18:43.489 --> 18:49.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is one small part of an $8
billion project, the most
extensive and expensive
improvement

18:49.996 --> 18:57.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ever to the B-61 nuclear bomb.
It's a nuclear test of sorts
without a mushroom cloud,
because

18:57.169 --> 19:02.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what's being tried out is a new
guidance system to increase
accuracy.

19:02.475 --> 19:05.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The first test mission was
flown by pilot Jeff Searcy.

19:05.611 --> 19:10.649 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAJ. JEFF SEARCY, U.S. Air
Force: We are able to enter in
coordinates into our system and

19:10.649 --> 19:15.121 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then transfer those coordinates
into the weapon now. And the
weapon is built to be able to

19:15.121 --> 19:17.356 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
guide to those coordinates.

19:17.356 --> 19:23.295 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NARRATOR: This is a B-61 bomb, a
lightweight two-stage
thermonuclear weapon.

19:23.295 --> 19:29.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: The B-61 was
designed and first built in the
early 1960s. As this vintage

19:29.235 --> 19:33.706 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Air Force film shows, it lacked
any of today high-tech guidance
systems, relying on a parachute

19:33.706 --> 19:37.710 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to give the plane time
to escape the blast.

19:37.710 --> 19:43.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A half-century later, it's still
the mainstay of the Air Force's
nuclear arsenal, long overdue

19:43.282 --> 19:46.752 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for an overhaul, argues Major
General Garrett Harencak.

19:46.752 --> 19:51.157 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAJ. GEN. GARRETT HARENCAK, U.S.
Air Force: These components age,
just like any component

19:51.157 --> 19:57.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would in an automobile or in an
appliance, and it has certain
aspects of it that just

19:57.163 --> 19:59.732 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have to be modernized.

19:59.732 --> 20:05.805 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: The "PBS
NewsHour" was given exclusive
and unprecedented access to the

20:05.805 --> 20:11.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
labs and facilities across the
country involved in the
multibillion-dollar makeover,
such

20:11.310 --> 20:14.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as the National Security Campus
in Kansas City, where crash
tests help determine the

20:14.780 --> 20:21.554 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
durability of key components.

20:21.554 --> 20:28.861 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The B-61 is just one program in
a $100 billion effort dubbed
stockpile stewardship, an
ambitious

20:28.861 --> 20:35.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
plan that includes modernizing
America's remaining arsenal of
1,500 nuclear bombs and
warheads.

20:35.768 --> 20:40.239 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
At Sandia National Laboratory in
New Mexico, senior engineer Brad
Boswell showed me the

20:40.239 --> 20:45.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
obsolete analog innards of the
old 1960s version of the bomb.

20:45.911 --> 20:49.615 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, one of the things that was
surprising to me was that we
still have nuclear weapons

20:49.615 --> 20:53.252 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
using vacuum tubes, like the
ones we had in our old TVs.

20:53.252 --> 20:54.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRAD BOSWELL, Sandia National
Laboratories: That is correct.

20:54.887 --> 21:01.494 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: And so this kind
vacuum tube is now part of this
printed circuit board?

21:01.494 --> 21:04.797 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRAD BOSWELL: That is correct.
As you look at this printed
circuit board, vacuum tubes

21:04.797 --> 21:09.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like this are replaced by the
smaller, commonly used
electronic, discrete components
that

21:09.568 --> 21:12.037 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
you see on these boards today.

21:12.037 --> 21:16.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: While many of
the components of the B-61 are
being upgraded and modernized,

21:16.709 --> 21:21.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the big change is the addition
of this tail fin kit, which
allows the bomb to be guided

21:21.780 --> 21:25.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to its target, a big improvement
over the old system that
deployed a parachute, which

21:25.851 --> 21:29.155 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
floated the bomb
down to the ground.

21:29.155 --> 21:36.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It won't make the bomb as
precise as a GPS-guided smart
bomb, but it will increase its
accuracy.

21:36.061 --> 21:41.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You might think that with all
their destructive power, nuclear
weapons wouldn't need to hit

21:41.300 --> 21:47.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a target dead center. But the
B-61 has a feature dubbed
dial-a-yield, which allows its
explosive

21:47.840 --> 21:53.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
force to be reduced. And when
combined with better accuracy,
that results in a weapon

21:53.112 --> 21:57.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
war-fighters might actually be
tempted to use on the
battlefield.

21:57.449 --> 22:01.453 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In his Washington office, Hans
Kristensen, with the Federation
of American Scientists,

22:01.453 --> 22:04.590 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
called up a Web site
to show me an example.

22:04.590 --> 22:07.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HANS KRISTENSEN, Federation of
American Scientists: Here you
have, the White House itself is
gone,

22:07.459 --> 22:12.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and so is much of the downtown
area, but a much smaller radius.

22:12.064 --> 22:17.836 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: Smaller blast
area, less radiation, fewer
casualties, all add up to a more
palatable

22:17.836 --> 22:22.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
last-resort option, argues
Kristensen, making the B-61 less
deadly, but, perversely, more

22:22.975 --> 22:24.977 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
dangerous.

22:24.977 --> 22:28.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HANS KRISTENSEN: It's more
likely that a military commander
will go to the president with
this

22:28.914 --> 22:33.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
weapon and say, Mr. President,
all our other options are out of
the question, but we have

22:33.052 --> 22:36.455 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a good one here that doesn't
pollute a whole lot.

22:36.455 --> 22:40.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: It's one thing
for an arms control advocates to
make that case, but another

22:40.125 --> 22:45.631 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
when the former top commander of
America's nuclear forces to
agree.

22:45.631 --> 22:49.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Retired Vice Chairman of the
Joint Chiefs Marine General
James Cartwright supports the

22:49.268 --> 22:54.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
B-61 upgrade, but can see how it
could change the calculus in a
crisis.

22:54.039 --> 22:56.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEN. JAMES CARTWRIGHT (RET.),
Former Vice Chairman of the
Joint Chiefs: If I can drive

22:56.108 --> 23:01.714 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
down the yield, drive down,
therefore, the likelihood of
fallout, et cetera, does that

23:01.714 --> 23:08.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
make it more usable in the eyes
of some -- some president or
national security
decision-making

23:08.053 --> 23:13.859 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
process? And the answer is, it
likely could be more usable.

23:13.859 --> 23:18.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: The Pentagon
argues making nuclear weapons
more usable makes them a more

23:18.731 --> 23:23.068 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
realistic threat, thereby
increasing their deterrent value
and decreasing the risk of

23:23.068 --> 23:26.272 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
miscalculation.

23:26.272 --> 23:30.142 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Donald Cook is a deputy
administrator at the National
Nuclear Security Administration,

23:30.142 --> 23:32.645 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
which is overseeing
the B-61 project:

23:32.645 --> 23:35.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DONALD COOK, Deputy
Administrator, National Nuclear
Security Administration: If we
have

23:35.180 --> 23:42.054 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a weapon that is lower-yield and
greater accuracy, and our
adversaries know that, it's my
own

23:42.054 --> 23:48.227 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
belief that that weapon then is
a more effective deterrent and
is, therefore, less likely to

23:48.227 --> 23:50.829 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ever be used in anger.

23:50.829 --> 23:56.235 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: The Pentagon is
careful to portray the new B-61
as basically the same

23:56.235 --> 24:01.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
old bomb with just a few more
modern parts. That's a key
point, since the Obama
administration

24:01.307 --> 24:05.878 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
had pledged not to build
new nuclear weapons.

24:05.878 --> 24:11.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But officials also stress
they're making the bomb safer
and more reliable. At Los Alamos

24:11.884 --> 24:16.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
National Laboratory, engineers
are testing a new high-explosive
material that's used

24:16.855 --> 24:26.131 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to trigger the nuclear chain
reaction in the B-61 warhead.
It's called insensitive high

24:26.131 --> 24:29.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
explosive, insensitive because
it's really hard to detonate,
just what you want in a

24:29.268 --> 24:32.638 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
nuclear warhead.

24:32.638 --> 24:39.745 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The standard for nuclear weapons
is always/never, as in, they
must always work when they
should,

24:39.745 --> 24:45.017 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and never when they shouldn't.
Critics of the B-61 say they
have no objection to making

24:45.017 --> 24:49.922 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
nuclear weapons safer, but they
allege the Energy Department
labs that rebuild the weapons

24:49.922 --> 24:53.726 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
have a financial motive,
lobbying Congress, sometimes
with government money, to
approve

24:53.726 --> 24:56.695 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
lucrative contracts.

24:56.695 --> 25:03.302 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Jay Coghlan is with Nuclear
Watch New Mexico, an
anti-nuclear watchdog group.

25:03.302 --> 25:06.538 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAY COGHLAN, Nuclear Watch New
Mexico: The American taxpayers
should know that the directors

25:06.538 --> 25:11.143 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
of these nuclear weapons
laboratories that are pushing
these extreme proposals actually

25:11.143 --> 25:15.180 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
have an inherent
conflict of interests.

25:15.180 --> 25:20.619 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're both the lab directors,
but at the same time they're the
presidents of corporations

25:20.619 --> 25:25.891 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
running the labs. It's in their
interests and their bottom line
to be able to have these

25:25.891 --> 25:28.761 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
life extension programs.

25:28.761 --> 25:33.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: At Sandia,
deputy laboratory director Steve
Rottler said his people believe

25:33.432 --> 25:36.702 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they are performing a vital
national security function.

25:36.702 --> 25:39.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
STEVE ROTTLER, Sandia National
Laboratories: We very much view
what we're doing as a public

25:39.471 --> 25:44.042 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
service. We approach it with
objectivity. We approach it with
the sober understanding

25:44.042 --> 25:47.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of what we're doing and the
impact of what that could mean
if these weapons were ever

25:47.045 --> 25:48.680 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
used.

25:48.680 --> 25:52.618 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: Critics like to
point out the estimated $20
million price tag for a

25:52.618 --> 25:59.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
single retooled B-61 is more
than if the 700-pound bomb were
made out of solid gold. And they

25:59.324 --> 26:02.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
argue the billions could be
better spent on more
conventional arms, weapons that
will

26:02.394 --> 26:06.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
be used every day.

26:06.432 --> 26:10.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That argument rankles Air Force
General Harencak, who says
deterring potential adversaries
is

26:10.035 --> 26:12.805 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a real return on investment.

26:12.805 --> 26:15.974 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAJ. GEN. GARRETT HARENCAK:
Eight-point-one billion dollars
is a lot of money, but what

26:15.974 --> 26:20.646 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you can't do is just take the
number of missiles and divide it
by 8.1 and say, OK, this is

26:20.646 --> 26:27.653 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the cost. This is a weapon that
is going to be used every single
day in a deterrent mission.

26:27.653 --> 26:31.523 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, when you add that over 40
years, find out, I think you
come to the realization that

26:31.523 --> 26:34.226 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it's a pretty good bargain
for the American people.

26:34.226 --> 26:38.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMIE MCINTYRE: The cost of the
program has already doubled once
from the initial estimate,

26:38.831 --> 26:45.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and one internal Pentagon review
back in 2012 suggested the final
cost could end up higher.

26:45.037 --> 26:50.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Whatever the price tag, the B-61
will be the Pentagon's most
expensive bomb project ever.

26:50.976 --> 26:56.548 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Jamie McIntyre, Eglin Air Force
Base, Florida.

26:56.548 --> 27:00.719 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: There's a lot
more about the remaking of
America's nuclear arsenal

27:00.719 --> 27:05.057 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
on our Web site. We have
extended excerpts of all the key
interviews, plus a photo essay,

27:05.057 --> 27:20.572 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
all that at PBS.org/NewsHour.

27:20.572 --> 27:22.741 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Stay with us.

27:22.741 --> 27:28.113 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour":
Making Sense of co-working
spaces in a freelance economy;

27:28.113 --> 27:31.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the first President Bush
slams Donald Rumsfeld and Dick
Cheney in Jon Meacham's

27:31.517 --> 27:34.019 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
"Destiny and Power."

27:34.019 --> 27:39.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, first, it's been more than
a year since actor and comedian
Robin Williams died. But

27:39.658 --> 27:43.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
new details shared this week by
his widow are calling attention
to a form of dementia

27:43.795 --> 27:46.632 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that has received little
public focus until now.

27:46.632 --> 27:49.234 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has the story.

27:49.234 --> 27:53.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: After Robin
Williams took his own life, his
press representative said

27:53.005 --> 27:57.142 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Williams was battling severe
depression. His widow, Susan
Schneider Williams, also said

27:57.142 --> 28:01.780 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back then that he was struggling
with depression and early stages
of Parkinson's disease

28:01.780 --> 28:06.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But this week, Mrs. Williams
told ABC News and "People"
magazine that an autopsy
revealed

28:06.051 --> 28:11.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
something else. He had what is
known as Lewy body dementia. She
described battling a mysterious

28:11.890 --> 28:16.662 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
set of symptoms for a year,
something she compared to
playing Whac-A-Mole -- quote --
"They

28:16.662 --> 28:20.165 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
present themselves like a
pinball machine," she said. "You
don't know exactly what you're

28:20.165 --> 28:23.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
looking at. I have spent this
last year trying to find out
what killed Robin, because we

28:23.769 --> 28:27.105 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
didn't know. He didn't know."

28:27.105 --> 28:30.976 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Joining me now to help us
understand more about this
disease is neurologist Dr. James

28:30.976 --> 28:33.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Galvin. He's a professor and
associate dean for clinical
research at Florida Atlantic

28:33.745 --> 28:34.947 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
University.

28:34.947 --> 28:39.952 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Dr. Galvin, thank
you for joining us.

28:39.952 --> 28:43.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seems that before this news
about Robin Williams broke, most
of us had never heard

28:43.855 --> 28:46.391 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of this disease. Can you tell
me a little bit more about it?

28:46.391 --> 28:49.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN, Florida
Atlantic University: Sure.

28:49.261 --> 28:54.199 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, Lewy body dementia may be
the most common disease you have
never heard of. It's the

28:54.199 --> 28:59.271 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
second most common cause of
memory problems after
Alzheimer's disease and affects
over

28:59.271 --> 29:05.877 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
1.3 million Americans. Its
predominant symptoms are a
progressive change in memory and
other

29:05.877 --> 29:12.884 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
thinking functions, signs of
Parkinson's, so, slow movement,
stiffness, balance problems,

29:12.884 --> 29:17.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
visual hallucinations, seeing
things that aren't there, like
little people or furry

29:17.923 --> 29:25.063 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
little animals, fluctuations in
levels of attention,
concentration, and, lastly, a
sleep

29:25.063 --> 29:28.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
disorder where people
act out their dreams.

29:28.033 --> 29:33.171 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Among that
huge array of symptoms, I'm
curious about the particular

29:33.171 --> 29:36.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
visual hallucinations you
described. Is that common for a
certain type of dementia to have

29:36.975 --> 29:39.244 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
such specific hallucinations?

29:39.244 --> 29:44.049 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN: It's very
common in Lewy body dementia.

29:44.049 --> 29:49.154 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Typically, if other dementias,
other memory problems develop
hallucinations, they're not

29:49.154 --> 29:54.459 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
until much later in the course
of the disease, and the
hallucinations are not so
well-formed.

29:54.459 --> 30:00.432 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What's particularly
characteristic of Lewy body
dementia are these very
well-formed hallucinations.

30:00.432 --> 30:04.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're usually not frightening
initially to the patient, but
they are very well-formed.

30:04.403 --> 30:07.673 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They usually can describe
exactly what they're seeing.

30:07.673 --> 30:13.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Is it partially
because -- it sounds like the
symptoms seem to mimic
Alzheimer's

30:13.111 --> 30:16.515 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and other diseases. Is that why
this is such a difficult to
diagnose?

30:16.515 --> 30:20.452 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DR. JAMES GALVIN:
That's exactly why.

30:20.452 --> 30:25.057 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Early on, some of the symptoms
may mimic other diseases, like
Alzheimer's if it's just the

30:25.057 --> 30:29.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
memory problems, Parkinson's
disease, if it's the movement
problems, or a psychiatric
disease

30:29.394 --> 30:33.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like schizophrenia if
it's the hallucinations.

30:33.031 --> 30:36.868 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It really takes an experienced
clinician to be able to be able
to put all the pieces together

30:36.868 --> 30:39.438 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and come up with the diagnosis.

30:39.438 --> 30:43.542 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, is this a
degenerative disease? And is
there any cure? Does it just

30:43.542 --> 30:47.012 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
get worse, or is there any
prognosis that is a hopeful one?

30:47.012 --> 30:49.715 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN: Well, it is a
progressive degenerative
disease, and we do not have a

30:49.715 --> 30:53.085 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
cure for it yet.

30:53.085 --> 30:58.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can effectively treat many of
the symptoms of the disease
using medicines for other
diseases.

30:58.090 --> 31:02.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, for example, we can use the
medicines that are used in
Alzheimer's disease and
Parkinson's

31:02.828 --> 31:08.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disease and schizophrenia to
treat the individual symptoms,
but I think it takes a very
careful,

31:08.567 --> 31:13.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
individualized approach to
decide which is the best regimen
of medicines for each patient.

31:13.371 --> 31:18.510 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Robin
Williams' widow described
battling these symptoms as akin
to playing

31:18.510 --> 31:22.180 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the game Whac-A-Mole. Is that
similar to what you have heard
from other parents, that it's

31:22.180 --> 31:26.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this very mysterious, hard thing
to pin down, you just don't know
what's coming at you?

31:26.518 --> 31:30.689 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN: It can be very
mysterious and very difficult
and challenging for the

31:30.689 --> 31:35.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
patients and the families and
for the clinicians, frankly.

31:35.427 --> 31:40.432 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As the symptoms begin to appear,
it really takes a while to kind
of sort out what is

31:40.432 --> 31:46.605 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going on. With the Lewy Body
Dementia Association, we had
conducted a survey over 950
caregivers

31:46.605 --> 31:52.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
to try to understand the
diagnostic experience. And what
we found was up to an 18-month
delay,

31:52.277 --> 31:55.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with patients seeing multiple
doctors over multiple visits,
before finally getting a

31:55.280 --> 31:57.916 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
correct diagnosis.

31:57.916 --> 32:01.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I understand
that there is some question
about whether people who

32:01.686 --> 32:07.325 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
suffer from Lewy body dementia
might be more at risk to harm
themselves or to commit suicide.

32:07.325 --> 32:11.196 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can you tell me a little bit
about that? Why would that be
and is that true?

32:11.196 --> 32:16.001 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN: Well, there's
no evidence that any of the
dementias, Lewy body dementia

32:16.001 --> 32:19.638 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or Alzheimer's disease, for that
matter, by themselves increase
the risk of people committing

32:19.638 --> 32:22.541 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
suicide.

32:22.541 --> 32:27.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, for some individuals, when
they hear they have a chronic
disease and they're trying

32:27.045 --> 32:31.850 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to deal with a chronic disease,
and maybe the diagnosis isn't
given or isn't correct

32:31.850 --> 32:36.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the time, and their symptoms
aren't responding, people can
make decisions to harm
themselves.

32:36.855 --> 32:39.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the disease itself is not
associated with a higher risk of
suicide.

32:39.658 --> 32:42.427 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: I see.

32:42.427 --> 32:46.765 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, looking forward, I mean, is
there any optimism that we're at
the cusp of a treatment

32:46.765 --> 32:49.401 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for this type of a disease?

32:49.401 --> 32:54.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN: Well, I think
there is great room for
optimism. We know more and more
about

32:54.172 --> 32:58.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the disease. We understand more
and more about the abnormal
proteins that aggregate or clump

32:58.777 --> 33:03.014 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
together, that cause the
changes in the brain.

33:03.014 --> 33:07.919 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so now this is beginning to
allow us to develop medications
that may have some effect.

33:07.919 --> 33:12.257 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Very recently, several companies
have made announcements that
they're beginning specific

33:12.257 --> 33:15.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
clinical trials to treat Lewy
body dementia. And these would
be the first medicines
specifically

33:15.594 --> 33:19.631 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
indicated for treating
Lewy body diseases.

33:19.631 --> 33:25.403 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think there is great
optimism. I think it's important
that patients remain hopeful

33:25.403 --> 33:29.040 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and families remain hopeful and
stay engaged and advocate for
their loved ones, so that

33:29.040 --> 33:32.277 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we can get more research funding
to develop new treatments.

33:32.277 --> 33:34.246 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: All right, Dr.
James Galvin of Florida Atlantic
University, thank you

33:34.246 --> 33:35.280 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
very much.

33:35.280 --> 33:42.587 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DR. JAMES GALVIN: Thank you.

33:42.587 --> 33:54.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: The latest
jobs report is due out tomorrow,
and, once again, it's expected

33:54.933 --> 33:58.703 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to show a large percentage of
people who are now
self-employed.

33:58.703 --> 34:03.508 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A New York-based start-up has
come up with a new business
model that rents office and

34:03.508 --> 34:08.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
work spaces to freelancers and
others. And it's growing. The
company announced a new

34:08.213 --> 34:11.349 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
round of fund-raising this week
as it opens more locations
around the country, as well

34:11.349 --> 34:14.619 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as in England, Israel
and the Netherlands.

34:14.619 --> 34:17.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the company's premise also
raises some fundamental
questions about the
transformation

34:17.789 --> 34:20.659 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the workplace.

34:20.659 --> 34:23.528 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Economics correspondent Paul
