subsequent invasion of Iraq,
among other things.

43:07.985 --> 43:13.591 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The book will not be published
until next week, but we have an
early look. For "Destiny

43:13.591 --> 43:18.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and Power: The American Odyssey
of George Herbert Walker Bush,"
Jon Meacham, the executive

43:18.062 --> 43:22.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
editor at Random House, relied
not only on extensive interviews
of the president's family,

43:22.667 --> 43:26.704 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
staff, and friends, but also on
the nearly daily audio diaries
the president recorded

43:26.704 --> 43:29.774 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
while in the White House.

43:29.774 --> 43:32.243 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Judy Woodruff talked with him
earlier this week for the
"NewsHour" Bookshelf.

43:32.243 --> 43:34.545 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Jon
Meacham, welcome.

43:34.545 --> 43:34.312 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON MEACHAM, Author, "Destiny
and Power: The American Odyssey
of George Herbert Walker

43:34.312 --> 43:36.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Bush": Thank you, Judy.

43:36.180 --> 43:42.053 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You had
extraordinary, maybe
unprecedented access to this
president, all

43:42.053 --> 43:46.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of his diaries, Barbara Bush's
diaries, the ability to
interview almost everybody in
the

43:46.257 --> 43:49.160 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
family. Why do you think they
trusted you with all this?

43:49.160 --> 43:52.497 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: Well, I hope they
felt that I would call it like I
saw it, which was the

43:52.497 --> 43:55.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
sort of the mandate
from the president.

43:55.600 --> 43:59.637 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A life of
privilege. I mean, he certainly
grew up in this family involved

43:59.637 --> 44:04.108 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in politics, great wealth, but
he also had a sense of
responsibility from a very early

44:04.108 --> 44:06.811 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
age. What do you
think shaped him?

44:06.811 --> 44:11.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: Well, you know, he
comes out of the same world of
noblesse oblige that

44:11.249 --> 44:15.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
shaped Theodore Roosevelt and
Franklin Roosevelt, and,
frankly, some of the founding
fathers.

44:15.152 --> 44:21.125 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You could argue that, culturally
and temperamentally, George H.W.
Bush has more in common with the

44:21.125 --> 44:26.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
founders than he does with his
successors generationally, in
terms of their life experience.

44:26.264 --> 44:31.769 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, his mother was hugely
important. She was very
religious and very competitive

44:31.769 --> 44:35.273 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in equal parts, I think,
it's safe to say.

44:35.273 --> 44:41.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he believed in the doctrine,
to whom much is given, much is
expected. What's really

44:41.045 --> 44:45.249 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
interesting, I think -- and I
hadn't realized this until I got
into Mrs. Bush's diary -- is

44:45.249 --> 44:49.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that there was an expectation,
there was a sense that he could
be president, that that

44:49.921 --> 44:55.760 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
possibility was within the realm
of the probable, as early as the
1950s.

44:55.760 --> 45:00.731 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You -- there's so
much about him and his
relationship, of course, with

45:00.731 --> 45:04.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his family, with Ronald Reagan,
who -- he was vice president to
Reagan for eight years.

45:04.535 --> 45:09.140 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, of course, his son went on
to be president for eight years.

45:09.140 --> 45:12.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he was very different from
them. And this touches on what
you said a minute ago. I mean,

45:12.643 --> 45:16.347 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his view of politics was more of
a pragmatic, rather than an
ideological...

45:16.347 --> 45:18.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JON MEACHAM: Absolutely.
Absolutely.

45:18.149 --> 45:20.818 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Labels are for cans,
he used to say.

45:20.818 --> 45:22.720 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

45:22.720 --> 45:27.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: And, you know, you
look at where we are now, and he
was part of this for a

45:27.558 --> 45:33.698 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
half-century. Mrs. Bush said in
1963, right before he first ran
for the Senate in 1964,

45:33.698 --> 45:37.268 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that the nuts will
never love him.

45:37.268 --> 45:41.038 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they were talking about the
John Birch Society back then.
The Republican base was

45:41.038 --> 45:47.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
always wary of George H.W. Bush.
In 1980, he called Reaganomics
voodoo economics.

45:47.745 --> 45:50.047 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

45:50.047 --> 45:53.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: In 1988, he lost
Iowa. You know, the party had
always -- the conservative part

45:53.951 --> 45:56.854 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of the party had always
been uneasy with him.

45:56.854 --> 46:01.959 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And he was the
one, after saying during the
campaign, "Read my lips, no new

46:01.959 --> 46:04.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
taxes," he went on to be elected
president, but when he saw the
budget deficit was out

46:04.662 --> 46:05.997 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of control, he raised taxes.

46:05.997 --> 46:08.132 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JON MEACHAM: Right.

46:08.132 --> 46:12.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mike Dukakis told me a great
story, that, when they met after
the election, Bush said,

46:12.870 --> 46:16.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"Well, I won't be able to raise
taxes in the first year." And
Dukakis thought: "In the

46:16.841 --> 46:20.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
first year? I just lost to this
guy saying he'd never raise
taxes."

46:20.411 --> 46:23.114 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: It was
interesting. You talked to him,
of course, about what happened
in

46:23.114 --> 46:28.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
his presidency and how he was
devastated by the loss. I mean,
he thought, I guess
understandably,

46:28.986 --> 46:31.088 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
that this was a
reflection of him.

46:31.088 --> 46:35.126 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JON MEACHAM: He thought he
was a failed president.

46:35.126 --> 46:40.431 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I open the book on election
night 1992, and I would argue
that, in many ways, the 20th

46:40.431 --> 46:45.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
century ended on November 3,
1992, when Bill Clinton, the
first baby boomer president,

46:45.936 --> 46:50.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
defeats George H.W. Bush, the
last World War II president.

46:50.541 --> 46:55.579 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Bush really just doesn't
quite get it, not in the sense
that we all remember he was

46:55.579 --> 46:59.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out of -- seemed out of touch
about the economy. That is not
-- that's not true. In fact, he

46:59.517 --> 47:03.354 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
knew the economy was going to
be a hugely important issue.

47:03.354 --> 47:09.093 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he says to his tape-recorded
diary, by himself, sitting in
the Houstonian Hotel:

47:09.093 --> 47:12.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
"Duty, honor, country, I always
thought that's what Americans
were made of, but, quite
plainly,

47:12.797 --> 47:15.199 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
it's not."

47:15.199 --> 47:22.039 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He was just subsumed with
anguish that he had not been
able to finish the job.

47:22.039 --> 47:26.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I do want to ask
you, Jon Meacham, about what he
says about his son, President

47:26.177 --> 47:30.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Bush 43, President
George W. Bush.

47:30.781 --> 47:38.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's very supportive, loves his
son. But you get him to talk
about how he was really
uncomfortable

47:38.155 --> 47:40.858 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
